snippet.textDisplay: It's all about servicing any car by the book and treating it well in general. Audi dips its car bodies and panels in zinc, seams are filled with protector, and the undercarriage is sprayed with more protection. Which is why that Audi still has a clean looking undercarriage for its mileage. My Audi does too. Of course any cast iron parts underneath will rust in time and can be inexpensively replaced. A 30 year old car can be in better shape than a 10 year old car all because of the attitude difference of their owners.

If that were mine I'd pay for the repairs because driving such a high-mileage vehicle is hilarious.

Having said that, I already run a 408,000-mile Peugeot Expert that I paid £200 for, then paid £1400 for a replacement engine and gearbox to be fitted, just for the laugh of looking at the odometer while I'm driving it. I also get a laugh from people's reactions when I tell them about it.
